&lt;h2 id=&#34;questions&#34;&gt;Questions&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Helpful questions to consider in choosing a Bible reading plan:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;What are you looking for? (Biblical knowledge or connection with God?)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How long do you want to read?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Ask God.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;my-thoughts&#34;&gt;My Thoughts&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Good overview and examples of the different types of plans.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;I appreciate his own personal emphasis on the Gospels.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Wisely warns about reading straight through the Bible. (&lt;a href=&#34;/thoughts/through&#34;&gt;I agree&lt;/a&gt;.)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;I look forward to his forth-coming plan!&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There seem to be five basic Bible reading plans:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;/tags/through&#34;&gt;Through&lt;/a&gt; the Bible ‚Äì Classic and straightforward, but not without &lt;a href=&#34;/thoughts/through&#34;&gt;challenges&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;/plans/daily-office&#34;&gt;Daily office lectionary&lt;/a&gt; ‚Äì Based on, for example, The Book of Common Prayer (2019) of the Anglican Church in North America (ACNA). (&lt;a href=&#34;https://northamanglican.com/a-new-daily-office-lectionary/&#34;&gt;Fascinating article&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;https://anglicancompass.com/category/anglicanism/daily-office-prayer/&#34;&gt;resources&lt;/a&gt; on the ACNA 2019 Daily Office.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Thematic ‚Äì Such as &lt;a href=&#34;https://my.bible.com/reading-plans&#34;&gt;those found at Bible.com&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Customized ‚Äì Like &lt;a href=&#34;https://bibleplan.org/plans/prof-horner/&#34;&gt;Professor Horner&amp;rsquo;s plan&lt;/a&gt; which has 10 chapters per day.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;DIY ‚Äì Using a generic Bible &lt;a href=&#34;https://visualunit.me/2010/12/14/bible-reading-chart/&#34;&gt;chart&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://bit.ly/3V4uAIu&#34;&gt;check sheet&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://biblicalspirituality.org/article/bible-reading/&#34;&gt;record&lt;/a&gt;, or app like BibleTracker (&lt;a href=&#34;https://apps.apple.com/us/app/my-bible-tracker/id1530078172&#34;&gt;iOS&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://bit.ly/3UA5Sz9&#34;&gt;Android&lt;/a&gt;), Bible Reading Assistant (&lt;a href=&#34;https://apps.apple.com/us/app/bible-reading-assistant/id1473756195&#34;&gt;iOS&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://bit.ly/3FxMfUr&#34;&gt;Android&lt;/a&gt;), Tracks ‚Äì Bible Companion (&lt;a href=&#34;https://apps.apple.com/us/app/tracks-bible-companion/id1231878723&#34;&gt;iOS&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://bit.ly/3VZibpN&#34;&gt;Android&lt;/a&gt;), or Daily Soul Bread (&lt;a href=&#34;https://apps.apple.com/us/app/daily-soul-bread/id1175130611&#34;&gt;iOS&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The classic and most common approach to a Bible reading plan is to read straight &lt;a href=&#34;/tags/through&#34;&gt;through&lt;/a&gt; ‚Äì often starting in January.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;While convenient, it keeps the reader outside of the New Testament until very late in the year. In addition, working through Leviticus in the dead of winter (at least in the northern hemisphere) is a double whammy that stifles many a good intention.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;guardrails&#34;&gt;Guardrails&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That said, any plan and any Scripture intake is better that no plan and no Scripture intake!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Therefore, utilizing a companion &lt;a href=&#34;/tags/devotional&#34;&gt;devotional&lt;/a&gt; or reading in community can be helpful ways to overcome this challenge.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;an-alternative&#34;&gt;An Alternative&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, using a plan that does not proceed sequentially through Scripture is the most direct approach. Specifically, a plan that loosely follows the church calendar (such as the &lt;a href=&#34;/plans/daily-office/&#34;&gt;daily office&lt;/a&gt;) is a natural way to cover the scope of Scripture by taking in a healthy balance of both the Old and New Testament.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But this is not without its own challenges. üò¨&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;After years of being involved in preparing a &lt;a href=&#34;/plans/ccci&#34;&gt;Bible reading plan for our church&lt;/a&gt;, the following are my currently desired &amp;ldquo;core characteristics&amp;rdquo; for a plan.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5 days a week (Weekdays)&lt;/strong&gt; ‚Äì This allows catch-up on the weekends.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2 chapters a day&lt;/strong&gt; ‚Äì Feels manageable, but provides space for a daily psalm or proverb (see below).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Through books of the Bible&lt;/strong&gt; ‚Äì Read books as they were intended.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Follows church calendar&lt;/strong&gt; (esp. Christmas and Easter) ‚Äì Provides preparation and focus.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Not &amp;ldquo;stuck&amp;rdquo; in Old Testament until end of year&lt;/strong&gt; ‚Äì Gives significant weight to the all-important shaping of the New Testament.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;bonus-values&#34;&gt;Bonus Values&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Daily Psalm or Proverb&lt;/strong&gt; ‚Äì Psalms are helpful in shaping a prayer life; Proverbs help cultivate wisdom.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In YouVersion&amp;rsquo;s Bible&lt;/strong&gt; ‚Äì Many of our people use the Bible app&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Devotional support&lt;/strong&gt; ‚Äì Can be helpful in explaining and applying the text (and thus not being discouraged by not understanding)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
